     "content": "The main components of a computer include the CPU (processor), RAM (memory), storage (SSD/HDD), motherboard, power supply, and input/output devices like keyboard, mouse, and monitor."},
    {"subject": "Computer Science", "title": "Driver (software)",
     "content": "A driver is a piece of software that allows the operating system to communicate with and control a specific hardware device, such as a printer, graphics card, or network adapter."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Motherboard",
     "content": "The motherboard is the main circuit board of a computer, connecting and allowing communication between the CPU, RAM, storage, and other components."},
    {"subject": "Computer Science", "title": "BIOS and UEFI",
     "content": "BIOS and UEFI are firmware that initialize hardware and start the operating system when a computer boots up. UEFI is the modern replacement for BIOS, offering faster boot times and more features."},
    {"subject": "Computer Science", "title": "Loop (programming)",
     "content": "A loop is a programming structure that repeats a block of code multiple times, until a certain condition is met, commonly implemented using 'for' or 'while' statements."},
    {"subject": "Databases", "title": "Database transaction",
     "content": "A database transaction is a sequence of operations performed as a single logical unit of work, which either fully completes (commit) or fully fails (rollback), ensuring data consistency."},
    {"subject": "Web Development", "title": "URL",
     "content": "A URL (Uniform Resource Locator) is the address used to locate a specific resource on the internet, typically including the protocol, domain name, and path (e.g., https://example.com/page)."},
    {"subject": "Web Development", "title": "Cookie (web)",
     "content": "A cookie is a small piece of data stored by a website in the user's browser, used to remember information like login sessions, preferences, or tracking data across visits."},
    {"subject": "Cybersecurity", "title": "Trojan horse (malware)",
     "content": "A Trojan horse is a type of malware disguised as legitimate software, which, once installed, can give attackers unauthorized access to or control over a computer system."},
    {"subject": "Artificial Intelligence", "title": "Chatbot",
     "content": "A chatbot is a computer program designed to simulate conversation with human users, often using rule-based logic or AI models like language models to generate responses."},

    # ---------------- ELECTRONIQUE FONDAMENTALE : COMPLEMENTS ----------------
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Resistor",
     "content": "A resistor is a passive electronic component that limits or controls the flow of electric current in a circuit, measured in ohms, often used to protect components or divide voltage."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Conductance",
     "content": "Conductance is a measure of how easily electric current flows through a material, the inverse of resistance, measured in siemens (S). Formula: $G = \\frac{1}{R}$."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Resistivity",
     "content": "Resistivity is a material property that quantifies how strongly it resists electric current flow, measured in ohm-meters, independent of the object's shape or size."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Potentiometer",
     "content": "A potentiometer is a variable resistor with three terminals, used to adjust voltage or resistance manually, commonly found in volume controls and dimmer switches."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Thermistor",
     "content": "A thermistor is a resistor whose resistance changes significantly with temperature, commonly used as a temperature sensor in electronic circuits."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Photoresistor (LDR)",
     "content": "A photoresistor (LDR, Light Dependent Resistor) is a component whose resistance decreases as the intensity of light falling on it increases, used in light-sensing circuits."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Fixed vs variable resistor",
     "content": "A fixed resistor has a constant, unchangeable resistance value, while a variable resistor (like a potentiometer) allows the resistance to be adjusted manually within a range."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Capacitance in series and parallel",
     "content": "For capacitors in series, the equivalent capacitance formula is $\\frac{1}{C_{eq}} = \\frac{1}{C_1} + \\frac{1}{C_2} + ...$. For capacitors in parallel, capacitances simply add: $C_{eq} = C_1 + C_2 + ...$."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Coil (inductor)",
     "content": "A coil (inductor) is a passive electronic component made of wire wound into loops, which stores energy in a magnetic field when current flows through it."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Inductance",
     "content": "Inductance is the property of an electrical conductor (like a coil) that opposes changes in current by generating a magnetic field, measured in henries (H)."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Electromagnet",
     "content": "An electromagnet is a type of magnet created by passing electric current through a coil of wire, producing a magnetic field that can be turned on or off by controlling the current."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "LED",
     "content": "An LED (Light Emitting Diode) is a semiconductor component that emits light when current flows through it in the forward direction, widely used for lighting and indicators due to its efficiency."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "MOSFET",
     "content": "A MOSFET (Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistor) is a type of transistor controlled by voltage at its gate terminal, widely used for switching and amplification in modern electronics."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Comparator",
     "content": "A comparator is an electronic circuit that compares two input voltages and outputs a signal indicating which one is higher, commonly built using an operational amplifier."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Oscillator",
     "content": "An oscillator is an electronic circuit that generates a repetitive, periodic signal (such as a sine or square wave) without needing an external input signal, used in clocks and radio transmitters."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Inverter (power electronics)",
     "content": "An inverter (in power electronics) converts direct current (DC) into alternating current (AC), commonly used in solar power systems and uninterruptible power supplies (UPS)."},

    # ---------------- ELECTRONIQUE NUMERIQUE : COMPLEMENTS ----------------
    {"subject": "Computer Science", "title": "Byte",
     "content": "A byte is a unit of digital information consisting of 8 bits, commonly used to represent a single character of text and as the basic unit for measuring data storage."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "AND gate",
     "content": "The AND gate is a fundamental digital logic component requiring every single input to be high before producing a high output; it behaves like two switches wired in series, where both must close to let current pass."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "OR gate",
     "content": "The OR gate is a fundamental digital logic component producing a high output as soon as any one input is high; it behaves like two switches wired in parallel, where closing either one lets current pass."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "NOT gate",
     "content": "The NOT gate, also called an inverter, is a fundamental digital logic component with a single input that simply flips or complements the signal: a high input becomes low, and a low input becomes high."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Digital register",
     "content": "A digital register is a small, fast storage location within a digital circuit or processor, made of flip-flops, used to temporarily hold binary data during processing."},

