     "content": "The Raspberry Pi is a small, affordable single-board computer capable of running a full operating system (like Linux), widely used for programming education, prototyping, and DIY electronics projects."},
    {"subject": "Embedded Systems", "title": "Arduino",
     "content": "Arduino is an open-source electronics platform based on simple microcontroller boards and software, widely used by beginners and hobbyists to build interactive electronic projects."},
    {"subject": "Embedded Systems", "title": "Interfacing sensors with a microcontroller",
     "content": "Interfacing a sensor with a microcontroller typically involves connecting the sensor's output pins to the microcontroller's input pins (analog or digital), then reading and processing the sensor's data in code."},

    # ---------------- ELECTRONIQUE : LOIS ET FORMULES ----------------
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Kirchhoff's current law",
     "content": "Kirchhoff's current law (KCL) states that the sum of currents entering a junction in a circuit equals the sum of currents leaving it, reflecting conservation of electric charge."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Kirchhoff's voltage law",
     "content": "Kirchhoff's voltage law (KVL) states that the sum of all voltages around any closed loop in a circuit equals zero, reflecting conservation of energy."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Electrical power",
     "content": "Electrical power is the rate at which electrical energy is transferred in a circuit, measured in watts. Formula: $P = V \\times I$."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Resistance in series and parallel",
     "content": "For resistors in series, the equivalent resistance is the sum: $R_{eq} = R_1 + R_2 + ...$. For resistors in parallel, it is calculated as $\\frac{1}{R_{eq}} = \\frac{1}{R_1} + \\frac{1}{R_2} + ...$."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "RC time constant",
     "content": "The RC time constant ($\\tau = R \\times C$) determines how quickly a capacitor charges or discharges through a resistor, representing the time to reach about 63% of the final voltage."},
    {"subject": "Electronics", "title": "Resistor color code",
     "content": "The resistor color code uses colored bands to indicate a resistor's value: each color represents a digit or multiplier, allowing the resistance value and tolerance to be read without a multimeter."},

